{{Infobox video game | released = 1997 | genre = Interactive CD-ROM }}
'''''Leonardo da Vinci''''' is a 1997 interactive [[CD-ROM]] game by [[Branded Entertainment Network|Corbis]], consisting of a "computerized viewing tool which permits the user to examine English translations of the [[Codex Leicester|Codex [Leicester]]] superimposed onto facsimiles of its pages".<ref name="wolfstonelaw.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.wolfstonelaw.com/leonardo_essay.html|title=Gary Wolfstone reviews Leonardo da Vinci Digitized|website=www.wolfstonelaw.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802003530/http://www.wolfstonelaw.com/leonardo_essay.html|archivedate=2015-08-02|df=}}</ref> The tool, known as Codescope, is licensed by Corbis.
==Development== In 1994, [[Bill Gates]] acquired the Codex Leicester.<ref name="wolfstonelaw.com"/> In 1997, Gates' privately held company Corbis released a CD-Rom version of the manuscript.<ref name="wolfstonelaw.com"/> On October 25, 1996 it was announced the game would be ready for the holiday season ([[Microsoft Windows]] in November and [[Macintosh]] in December<ref name="thefreelibrary.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Corbis+Announces+%22Leonardo+da+Vinci%22+CD-ROM.-a018795189|title=Corbis Announces "Leonardo da Vinci" CD-ROM. - Free Online Library|website=www.thefreelibrary.com}}</ref>), but this was ultimately postponed.<ref name="thefreelibrary.com"/> The game was one in a line of educational/entertainment CD-ROMs with subjects including [[Paul Cézanne]], [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], and the [[Manhattan Project]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/400162/setting-a-standard-in-multimedia-software/|title=Setting A Standard In Multimedia Software|first=Wade|last=Roush|publisher=}}</ref> The game's promotion was kick-started by being featured in a Da Vinci exhibition at the [[American Museum of Natural History]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edge.org/conversation/doug_rowan-the-curator|title=The Curator - Edge.org|website=www.edge.org|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421031456/https://www.edge.org/conversation/doug_rowan-the-curator|archivedate=2018-04-21|df=}}</ref>
==Content== The title contains the Codex Leceister, as well as a virtual gallery of Leonardo’s major paintings, plus his drawings, manuscripts, and lost works.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sumscorp.com/img/file/1997_Review_Leonardo_da_Vinci_CD_ROM_Corbis.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2018-04-20 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809124459/http://www.sumscorp.com/img/file/1997_Review_Leonardo_da_Vinci_CD_ROM_Corbis.pdf |archivedate=2017-08-09 |df= }}</ref> Players can view the Codex in the original mirror-script Italian, a reversed “normal” view, a transcription of the original Italian, and a modern English translation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.xconomy.com/boston/2008/05/09/an-elegy-for-the-multimedia-software-stars/attachment/the-codescope-from-corbiss-leonardo-da-vinci-cd-rom/|title=The Codescope, from Corbis's Leonardo da Vinci CD-ROM - Xconomy|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421164217/https://www.xconomy.com/boston/2008/05/09/an-elegy-for-the-multimedia-software-stars/attachment/the-codescope-from-corbiss-leonardo-da-vinci-cd-rom/|archivedate=2018-04-21|df=}}</ref> ''Leonardo Da Vinci'' is a coffee-table-book type game.<ref name="forbes.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/free_forbes/1997/1103/6010046a.html|title=Tasteful. Unprofitable. Microsoft?|website=www.forbes.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421032320/https://www.forbes.com/free_forbes/1997/1103/6010046a.html|archivedate=2018-04-21|df=}}</ref>
==Critical reception== Lawyer Gary L. Wolfstone deemed the project "impressive" and "interpretive".<ref name="wolfstonelaw.com"/> ''[[Computer Shopper (US magazine)|Computer Shopper]]'' praised the title's ease of use and slick production values.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19135486.html|title=Corbis' Leonardo da Vinci: an old master in a new medium. (Corbis Corp) (Software Review)(Brief Article)(Evaluation)|date=1 March 1997|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421030601/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19135486.html|archivedate=21 April 2018|df=}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' felt the game "exemplif[ies] the strengths and weaknesses of multimedia at its current, immature state of development".<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19323334.html|title=Leonardo da Vinci. (CD-ROM book) (Software Review)(Brief Article)|date=19 April 1997|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421031313/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19323334.html|archivedate=21 April 2018|df=}}</ref> ''ATPM'' felt the game would hold the interest of both novice and scholar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpm.com/4.06/page13.shtml|title=ATPM 4.06 - Review: Leonardo da Vinci CD-ROM|website=www.atpm.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409210339/http://www.atpm.com/4.06/page13.shtml|archivedate=2016-04-09|df=}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' deemed it one of the better art-history CD-ROMs, despite some oversights in features and interface.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/library/cyber/mirapaul/1226mirapaul.html|title=Backwards or Forwards, the CD-Rom of Leonardo's Codex Comes Up a Winner|website=archive.nytimes.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094443/https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/library/cyber/mirapaul/1226mirapaul.html|archivedate=2018-04-21|df=}}</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' explained that the experience of playing the game was "as if Leonardo can suddenly speak".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/1996/11/corbis/|title=In His Image|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421031649/https://www.wired.com/1996/11/corbis/|archivedate=2018-04-21|df=}}</ref> ''[[de Volkskrant]]'' felt that the game supported Gates' thesis that computer technology could be a form of art.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/archief/gladjes-maar-leonardo-da-vinci-past-goed-op-een-cd-rom~a509728/|title=Gladjes, maar Leonardo da Vinci past goed op een cd-rom|website=de Volkskrant|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421031511/https://www.volkskrant.nl/archief/gladjes-maar-leonardo-da-vinci-past-goed-op-een-cd-rom~a509728/|archivedate=2018-04-21|df=}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote that while Da Vinci is a popular subject for video games, this title "beats them all".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB847323768795403500|title=New CD-ROM Titles Get You Acquainted With FDR, da Vinci|first=Walter S.|last=Mossberg|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421031233/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB847323768795403500|archivedate=2018-04-21|df=}}</ref>
Corbis did not earn a profit from the game.<ref name="forbes.com"/>
