'''Miriam Beerman''' (born 1923) is an [[Americans|American]] [[Painting|painter]] and [[Printmaking|printmaker]].

Beerman was born in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]], where she later earned her BFA from the [[Rhode Island School of Design|Rhode Island School for Design]].  After earning her degree, she studied with various established artists including [[Yasuo Kuniyoshi]] at the [[Art Students League of New York|Art Students League]] in [[New York City|NYC]], with [[Adja Yunkers]] at [[The New School|the New School for Social Research]] in NYC, and [[Stanley William Hayter]] at Atelier 17 in [[Paris]], [[France]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Heller|first=Jules|title=North American Women Artists of the Twentieth Century: A Biographical Dictionary|year=1995|publisher=Garland Publishing, Inc.|location=New York and London|page=57}}</ref>

Although Beerman maintains the gestural brushstrokes of the [[Abstract expressionism|abstract expressionists]], her work focuses on bestial characters who convey the intense emotion found in her images.  Her work includes automatic gestures, vivid colors, and [[Stippling|stippled]] textures that help evoke the feeling of devastation.  Some of her themes include biblical plagues, [[the Holocaust]], Hiroshima, and nuclear threat.<ref>Weld, Alison. "Miriam Beerman On Line Gallery." Miriam Beerman On Line Gallery. Miriam Beerman, n.d. Web. 12 June 2013.</ref>

The breadth of Beerman's career is evident through her grants, awards, and exhibitions list.  Some include a CAPS grant from [[New York State Council on the Arts]] (1971), the [[Childe Hassam]] purchase award from the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] (1977), the Camargo Foundation Award (1980), a distinguished artist grant from the [[New Jersey State Council on the Arts]] (1987), and a 40-year retrospective of her work, held at the [[New Jersey State Museum|State Museum of New Jersey]] in [[Trenton, New Jersey|Trenton]] (1991).<ref>Who's Who in American Art. 20th ed. R.R. Bowker Co., 1993-1994.</ref> Her work has been exhibited globally, including at the [[Corcoran Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]], and at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|NY]].

In 2000, Beerman was an Artist's Book Resident at the [[Women's Studio Workshop]] in [[Rosendale, New York]]. During her residency, Beerman published ''Faces'', a limited-edition portfolio of eight drypoint prints with text from ''[[The Notebooks of Malte Laurids Brigge]]'' by [[Rainer Maria Rilke]].  The images are rough, humorous and tragic, echoing the artist’s humanistic concerns.<ref>“Faces.” Women’s Studio Workshop. Retrieved 2014-01-31.</ref>

Beerman received awards and honors from Pollock Krasner Foundation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pkf-imagecollection.org/artist/Miriam_Beerman/works/5134?list_url=/artists?sort=AE&page=4&letter=B|title=Miriam Beerman {{!}} Corridors of the Soul {{!}} 1987 {{!}} Pollock Krasner Image Collection|website=www.pkf-imagecollection.org|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref> Joan Mitchell Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://joanmitchellfoundation.org/artist-programs/artist-grants/painter-sculptors/1994/miriam-beerman|title=Artist Programs » Artist Grants|last=Foundation|first=Joan Mitchell|website=joanmitchellfoundation.org|language=en|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref> and more.  She also received an alumni award from Rhode Island School of Design in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://our.risd.edu/post/113993559999/honoring-lifetime-achievement|title=Honoring Lifetime Achievement|website=Our RISD|language=en|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref> In 2015 Beerman had a collage retrospective at Lawrence University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.lawrence.edu/news/2015/09/miriam-beerman-collages-print-portfolio-focused-on-social-injustice-featured-in-new-wriston-galleries-exhibition.html|title=Miriam Beerman collages, print portfolio focused on social injustice featured in new Wriston Galleries exhibition – Lawrence University News|website=blogs.lawrence.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref> Miriam Beerman, Expressing the Chaos, a film by Jonathan Gruber, was also released in 2015. The film was shown on PBS and on  Dutch and New Zealand T.V.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressingthechaos.com/the-film|title=expressing the chaos {{!}} THE FILM|website=expressing-the-chaos|language=en|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref>

