{{refimprove|date=July 2014}} {{Infobox University |name= University of Juba |image= [[File:University of Juba.jpg|Juba University Seal|200px]] |established= 1977 |type= [[Public university|Public]] |vice_chancellor= Prof. [[John Akec]] |city= [[Juba]] |country= [[South Sudan]] |diploma= |undergrad= |postgrad= |master= |phd= |staff= |free_label= Campuses Juba Centre, Bilinyiang, Kadaro (Khartoum), Omdurman. |free= |website= [http://jubauni.net/ University of Juba Website] }}
'''University of Juba''' ({{lang-ar|جامعة جوبا}}<!--For when it was a part of Sudan-->) is a [[public university]] located in [[Juba, South Sudan|Juba]], [[South Sudan]], founded in 1975 in response to the need for higher education in southern areas of [[Sudan]]. Due to the [[Second Sudanese Civil War]] (1983 - 2005), the university relocated to [[Khartoum]], for safety of staff, students and infrastructure. In 2006, the government at that time agreed to change the name of the university to [[Juba National University]]. Following the attainment of [[independence]] by South Sudan in July 2011, the university has relocated back to Juba, where it was founded. The university gives instruction in the [[English language]].
==History== The University of Juba was established in 1975 in [[Juba, South Sudan]], while the city was still part of Sudan. The university admitted the first students in the 1977 school year. In 2006, while still part of Sudan, the university temporarily relocated to Sudan's capital of [[Khartoum]]. Following the [[History of South Sudan#Independence|independence of South Sudan]].
==Public universities== {{asof|April 2014}}, the university is one of the seven public universities in South Sudan, the other six being the [[Upper Nile University]] in [[Malakal]] but currently relocated in Juba due to on going civil war,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sudantribune.com/Rumbek-University-to-be-opened,32079 |title=Partial Listing of South Sudan's Public Universities |access-date=19 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726175548/https://www.sudantribune.com/Rumbek-University-to-be-opened,32079 |archive-date=26 July 2011 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Rumbek University]], [[Rumbek]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201106291392.html |title=Vice Chancellor of Rumbek University is Professor Professor Matthew Atem Aduol |access-date=2 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020072044/http://allafrica.com/stories/201106291392.html |archive-date=20 October 2012 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the [[University of Bahr El-Ghazal]], [[Wau, South Sudan|Wau]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.iime.org/database/africa/sudan.htm |title=List of Medical Schools in Sudan & South Sudan |access-date=2 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306145139/http://www.iime.org/database/africa/sudan.htm |archive-date=6 March 2014 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the [[University of Northern Bahr El-Ghazal]], [[Aweil]],<ref>[http://www.sudanradio.org/new-established-university-northern-bahr-el-ghazal-open-october University of Northern el Ghazal Opening In 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226213639/http://www.sudanradio.org/new-established-university-northern-bahr-el-ghazal-open-october |date=26 December 2015 }}</ref> and [[John Garang Memorial University]] in [[Bor, South Sudan|Bor]].
